abstract = {Outcomes: 1. Report and discuss differences in hospice and palliative medicine (HPM) fellows’ reported willingness to discuss versus provide recommendations regarding use of medical cannabis 2. Integrate evidence for medical cannabis into evaluating the options for managing patient symptoms
Purpose
Medical cannabis is increasingly considered for palliation of pain, neuropathy, nausea/vomiting, anorexia, and other symptoms. We aimed to determine whether training in hospice and palliative medicine (HPM) adequately prepares fellows to counsel patients about medical cannabis.
Methods
A previously validated questionnaire was adapted for HPM fellows. Domains included fellows’ practices regarding cannabis recommendations in treating serious illness and their knowledge of its effectiveness and risks as compared with standard treatments. From February through June 2022, 167 U.S. HPM fellowship programs were sent a survey to distribute to fellows.
Results
Forty-four programs from 19 states participated; of the 142 trainees across these programs, 58 responded (response rate of 41%). Participants included 72% female; 59% White, 22% Asian, and 4% Hispanic. Of respondents, 83% reported receiving formal training regarding medical cannabis; 66% reported discussing medical cannabis with more than five patients in the preceding year; 29% recommended medical cannabis to more than five patients in the preceding year. Only 20%, however, felt sufficiently informed to issue cannabis-related clinical recommendations. HPM fellows who reported prior training in medical cannabis were more likely to feel sufficiently informed to discuss cannabis recommendations (risk ratio: 10.07; 95% CI, 1.46 to 78.4) and to recommend medical cannabis to patients (risk ratio: 2.57; 95% CI, 1.04 to 6.37). Fellows rate cannabis as equally or more effective than conventional treatments for the following symptoms: anorexia/cachexia (60%), nausea/vomiting (45%), pain (25%), and neuropathic pain (19%).
Conclusion
Most HPM fellows report formal training in the use of medical cannabis. Over half of trainees reported discussing medical cannabis with patients, but few considered themselves sufficiently informed to make cannabis-related clinical recommendations. These results suggest both a need for expanded high-quality evidence for medical cannabis in palliative care and for improved formal education for HPM fellows.}
